{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2c5eeeb5-ebd4-4270-9bdd-a827502bb20f","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the OS automatically generates a `.ips` crash report. You can find it in:\n\n1. **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for user-launched processes\n2. **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — for system-wide crashes\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump):\n\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Run your app again to reproduce — core file appears in /cores/\n```\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash log contains the native backtrace. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames, I can help with that using the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill — just share the `.ips` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5e167046-4b77-4036-ad39-515ca8786746","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":307,"requestId":"6807:294035:18CBE35:1BD2DE3:69FD41A6"},"id":"580c4ab0-0d45-48b4-8f9d-721a086f5a9d","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:51:44.660Z","parentId":"40462059-ad21-4204-8c8e-244612be8acc"}
